Also has a heavy, tungsten guide rod assembly, reducing recoil significantly; original guide rod assembly included as well. It has the "plug" installed on the grip for smoother magazine feeds. Comes with a total of 5 17 rd magazines, a 5.11 tactical holster w/paddle & belt attachments, an El Paso Saddlery leather holster & a Fobus 2-mag holster. Also the original box and everything that it came with it from Glock. I've put around 350-400 flawless rounds through it & I never have the time to shoot it anymore so I'm looking for something that I can carry. I have a valid Ohio concealed carry license, FYI. The Glock is kept immaculately clean and shows no wear whatsoever. I'm looking to trade, not pressed to sell, but I suppose $850 could take it. What I'm really looking for is a QUALITY, CONCEALABLE firearm & I'd prefer it come with, at a minimum, a concealment holster & ammo. I have plenty of quality hollow point ammunition to trade for yours, so it'll be fair. I don't want $700. I don't want $800. I'll take a revolver of less value with the extras mentioned so long as there's cash involved to even up the trade. title: For Sale/Trade:  AK-47 needs a new home
postcontent:
The holiday season is upon us, it's a time for love, caring and sharing. What better way to celebrate than by sharing your home with another? Have you looked into your half-empty safe lately and seen just how lonely those AR's are? It's common knowledge that black rifles require constant companionship to lead a full and healthy life. 

 I know that money can also be a factor with people this time of the year. With buying little Johnny a new PS7 and Suzy insisting on the latest Ipad 12, it doesn't take long until your wallet is screaming "no mas". 

Have you considered adoption?

This poor semi-automatic rifle is looking for a good home. It's originally from the mean streets of Romania where it spent a hardened life surviving on copper-clad 7.62x39 bullets and abusive powder. It landed in America with nothing more than cosmoline in it's pockets and a gleam of hope in its barrel. It was once fostered by Century Arms, where it was tortured and branded as a WASR 10/63. 

 Give this rifle the home that it deserves.The adoption fee is a mere $775, to ensure that it does go to a good, providing home. 

Please, won't you help?

It has an antique treen wooden dice cup and an antique wooden small roulette wheel that turns. It also has an antique deck of Samuel Hart cards (complete set) in good but used condition. In the bottom drawer you can find 2 matching Wizard cuff holders (pat date 1888) and an antique pair of eyeglasses. The overall condition of the case and contents is in good but used condition. This is a very cool set that I know you won't be disappointed in this set.
